+## Tao trigger map and role table
+
+[VERIFIED] Tao's reduced delayed-transfer circuit uses five causally linked roles:
+
+| Tao variable | Exact role | Meaning for the trigger question | Why it is unavoidable |
+| --- | --- | --- | --- |
+| `a` / `X1,n` | `a1(t) = u_{σ1}(k1,t)` | current carrier | needed to measure trigger smallness relative to the active carrier and to record back-reaction |
+| `b` / `X2,n` | `a2(t) = u_{σ2}(k2,t)` | slow clock / gate opener | needed because the trigger is delayed by amplifier input from the clock |
+| `c` / `X3,n` | `a3(t) = u_{σ3}(k3,t)` | tiny trigger | the theorem-facing trigger variable |
+| `d` / `X4,n` | `a4(t) = u_{σ4}(k4,t)` | conduit / rotor leg | needed because post-threshold trigger visibility is through the conduit/rotor activation |
+| `ã` / `X1,n+1` | `a5(t) = u_{σ5}(k5,t)` | next carrier / output | needed because successful delayed transfer must become visible at the handoff output |
+
+[CHECKED] This already answers the first helpful question. A "tiny delayed trigger" cannot be defined honestly as less than a five-role object if "dynamically decisive" means what it means in Tao's mechanism. The trigger is only meaningful through a carrier scale, a clocked amplifier, a conduit, and an output handoff.
+
+[VERIFIED] The exact representation is the helical Fourier basis on a finite sign-closed support
+
+```text
+S(K,σ) = {(kj,σj), (-kj,-σj) : j = 1,...,5},
+```
+
+with exact amplitude equations
+
+```text
+(∂t + ν|kj|^2) aj = Fj^des(a) + Fj^int-leak(a) + Fj^ext-leak(u).
+```
