+# Exploration 001 Summary
+
+- Goal: decide whether Tao's tiny delayed trigger can be turned into one preferred exact-NS object that is genuinely narrower than the already-killed five-role singleton circuit, or whether every honest formulation collapses back to that object or to a non-canonical packet backup.
+- What I tried: used the Tao delayed-transfer reconstruction, the predecessor exact helical definition, the singleton non-embeddability result, the spectator-coupling and coefficient-rigidity notes, the packet non-canonicity note, and the missionary learnings to test whether a trigger-only object survives the definition gate.
+- Outcome: succeeded.
+- Gate verdict: `fail`.
+- Stop category: `model-level negative candidate`.
+- One key takeaway: the only faithful exact trigger object is just the prior five-role helical hypergraph with `a3` highlighted, so this strategy has no new canonical test object beyond the already-killed singleton model.
+- Leads worth pursuing: none inside this strategy. A future precursor mission would need to define and defend a canonical exact packet model first.
+- Unexpected findings:
+  - narrowing the question from "near-closed Tao circuit" to "tiny delayed trigger" does not actually shrink the faithful exact object;
+  - the trigger remains meaningful only through the full clock/amplifier/conduit/handoff chain;
+  - the packet backup fails all four canonization checks at once: support, projection, leakage/back-reaction bookkeeping, and restoration to exact NS language.
+- Computations worth doing later: none unless a new canonical packet support, projection, and exact-network restoration rule are proposed first.
